 Please feel free to share your feedback with us during the Q&A section.

49
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 And now, without further ado, please join me in welcoming our guest speaker,

50
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,000
 Professor Peter Phillip.

51
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:00,000
 [Applause]

52
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:07,000
 Thank you.

53
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 Good evening.

54
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 It is great to be here.

55
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 Thank you very much to CGST for inviting me to come over to Hong Kong

56
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 and to talk to you about Balaam and his donkey.

57
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 I look forward especially to the response because I think there will be something

58
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:30,000
 that outplays anything that I can say.

59
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 But that is something to wait for.

60
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:39,000
 The question is really about human wisdom and how it comes to explore

61
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 computer wisdom or computer intelligence.

62
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
 How do we get from one to the other?

63
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,000
 And what is the problem around co-intelligence, the way in which AI

64
00:04:52,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 can really be a co-intelligent being or persona like us?

65
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 Over the years, my own research work has focused on biblical studies,

66
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 first of all, then theology, mission, and now especially around digital

67
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 and the development of a theological understanding of the digital.

68
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 What do we mean by the digital?

69
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 What has Christianity got to do with the digital?

70
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 What has theology got to do with the digital?

71
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:32,000
 Trying to explore current religious practice within digital culture.

72
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 We almost had a conversation over the meal beforehand about sacraments online,

73
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:41,000
 but we didn't quite get there.

74
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 I must speak to you sometime, Celine, on that.

75
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 Digital theology, a new field, entails an analyzing the impact of the digital

76
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
 upon the theological.

77
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 The impact of both the theological and digital on our current social reality.

78
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 What we might call a cultural technique, as Ellul would have put it,

79
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 or a social space in Lefebvre's terms, perhaps in Latour, an actor network.

80
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 What he called was that the world is composed of dynamic, shifting networks

81
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:38,000
 where humans, non-humans, objects, ideas, and technologies all act as actors

82
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 or actants.

83
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:48,000
 Well, the one in vogue at the moment is Baudu, who talked about that kind of

84
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 meshing of technology and society as a form of habitus.

85
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 Pierre Baudu, habitus and field.

86
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 And indeed his ideas have been picked up recently in two new key books

87
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 in the imaginaries of AI and the digital.

88
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 Massimo Araldi's Machine Habitus or Alberto Ramelli's Digital Habitus.

89
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 Whilst Ramelli warns the reader constantly about the dangers of AI,

90
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:35,000
 Araldi is dazzled by it, dazzled by its potential,

91
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 its potential to solve all of our problems.

92
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 He argues, like all the tech bros in America, it's here and so we have to

93
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 make use of it or we're wasting progress.

94
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 We're being left behind, not maximising our progress towards technological

95
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 superiority or excellence.

96
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 A bit like Ethan Mollick's Co-intelligence.

97
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 Have you read this one yet?

98
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 Which warns us about the limitations of AI.

99
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 It doesn't think like we do, we're told.

100
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 But at the same time calls upon we, the readers, to act as though it were

101
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 some form of quasi-human intelligence.

102
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 Co-intelligence.

103
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 And Mollick tells us, one of the biggest read books in the AI field,

104
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 says just pretend it's a being, pretend it's a person like you or me

105
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 and everything will be alright.

106
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 Such are the proper concerns of a digital theologian in 2026.

107
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 In Numbers 22 in the Bible, Balaam, who is either a contemporary of Moses

108
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 or a relic of Canaanite religion from an earlier time,

109
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 is portrayed as a Gentile soothsayer hired by King Balak to curse the Israelites.

110
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 One Jewish site calls him a prophetically crippled buffoon.

111
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 I wonder if the AI got that right.

112
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 Less able than the donkey he is riding to see the angel about to pierce him with a sword.

113
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,000
 But we know the story.

114
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 The donkey has to explain to Balaam about that an angel with a large sword is blocking their way

115
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 while Balaam threatens to beat the donkey to death as it crushes his leg against the wall

116
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:19,000
 trying to keep him away from the angel.

117
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:29,000
 In this paper today, I want to play on the idea that Balaam's donkey is a version of AI

118
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 and on Balaam as a theologian or a preacher in the age of AI.

119
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 The donkey seems to be the cheap and easy way to find what God is up to

120
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 rather than having to go to God direct.

121
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:59,000
 Balaam relies upon the donkey to feed information from God to him.

122
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:06,000
 Prompt the donkey, don't risk going direct to Yahweh.

123
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 And perhaps that's what we'll be doing soon as we prompt our sermons and create sermons from AI

124
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 rather than going and asking God what he wants us to preach on.

125
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 The donkey acts as a form of divine revelation, a quick prompt and response process

126
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:41,000
 like grok or claude or chat GPT to help Balaam understand about what's going on.

127
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 A wise word in his ear perhaps.

128
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 Although the whole problem is that that process sidesteps the fact that Balaam has another way

129
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 a more regular source for divine wisdom that he tends to ignore.

130
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 That is the ability to interact directly with Yahweh himself.

131
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:19,000
 Since Yahweh seems to interact directly with this archaic secular soothsayer

132
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 just as he interacts with Moses, the holy man of God.

133
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:34,000
 So a bit like AI, the donkey acts as a shortcut for sermon writing.

134
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:41,000
 A way to hear what God is saying without going directly to God himself.

135
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:45,000
 A providential donkey.

136
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 And Balaam the prophet can be connected with Yahweh and yet so disconnected

137
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 that his donkey needs to remind him of God's very presence through the angel in front of him.

138
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:12,000
 It's that kind of confused and confusing relationship that I think we might have with AI in all its forms

139
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:21,000
 and particularly AI and sermon preparation and other applications around the church.

140
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:26,000
 Where is God in all of this?

141
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 Is AI the word of God?

142
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 Or the word of society?

143
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 Or the word of Elon Musk?

144
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 Or our own confused word?

145
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:45,000
 Or just the words of a foolish donkey?

146
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:52,000
 Is the donkey and so possibly AI God's revelation to us?

147
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:55,000
 Is it God speaking to us through him?

148
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 Through the donkey, through AI, whoever him is?

149
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 Or is this just a silly story offering a confused picture of revelation?

150
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:17,000
 And has God got better ways to talk to each one of us rather than through the clumsiness of donkey AI?

151
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:25,000
 See part of what we are being told at the moment by the tech bros in the States and wherever they may be

152
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 is that AI is the normative way we do research.

153
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:41,000
 It's the normative way that we write papers, to submit to academic journals, to find information,

154
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:55,000
 to summarise meetings, to plan events, to write our sermons, to create worship songs, to do biblical studies.

155
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 But of course that's like the sales gimmick in the Wizard of Oz.

156
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:04,000
 The snake oil salesman trick.

157
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:06,000
 The panacea.

158
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 Sign here, everything will be well.

159
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:19,000
 Balaam has refused to listen to God's normative engagement with him.

160
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 Which is through direct intervention, by circumstances, by changes to details, by direct orders.

161
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,000
 Balaam resists the normal channels that God engages him with.

162
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:43,000
 God gets a donkey to talk to him, an irregular means, an abnormal means, out of the ordinary according to the Bible.

163
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:52,000
 That normal way, as seen through Moses, whose orthodox encounters with God surround the story of Balaam,

164
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:58,000
 is through the presence of God himself, through his spirit, through God's voice,

165
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:03,000
 through meditation on our bed through the night, the psalmist says.

166
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:09,000
 Through changes in circumstances, events, answers to prayer, signs and wonders on the way.

167
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 God speaks to us in plenty of ways.

168
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:25,000
 My point in this paper is that the AI tech bros, the AI industry,

169
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:32,000
 are making a bid for their algorithms, their large language models, their LLMs,

170
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 to be the be-all and end-all inspiration machines for the 21st century.

171
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:47,000
 A bit like Microsoft did with the paperclip.

172
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:56,000
 I think that's getting things mixed up completely.

173
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 Back in the early 20th century, no, it seems, in our research around the Bible, social media and digital culture,

174
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 we analysed over 15 years of data and noted a gradual shift away from the citation of propositional verses,

175
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:22,000
 verses which were about the propositions about God and the Bible,

176
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:28,000
 and towards the citation of therapeutic verses.

177
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 So in print culture, John 3.16 was the main verse, the preeminent verse in the pre-digital era.

178
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:55,000
 A propositional verse explaining the salvific impact of God's gift of his own son.

179
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:02,000
 But God is the agent in that verse, for God so loved the world.

180
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:13,000
 Christ is the sacrificial victim, and the world, particularly believers, are the beneficiaries of his death.

181
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:21,000
 But in the digital age, with the advent of digital platforms such as YouVersion and Bible Gateway,

182
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:30,000
 which were created through Facebook and other models, the most searched, shared and cited verses shifted to these texts,

183
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:38,000
 the blue ones, the ones that are described as akin to moralistic, therapeutic deism.

184
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:44,000
 Classically, Jeremiah 29.11, all the way at the top.

185
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:56,000
 "For I know the plans I have for you, declares the Lord, plans to prosper you and not to harm you, plans to give you hope and a future."

186
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:04,000
 We found that such verses no longer talked about God's activity to save the world,

187
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 but rather of the moral and therapeutic impact of the Judeo-Christian tradition on the well-being of humanity.

188
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:23,000
 In such texts, especially seen in the popularity of verses from the beginning of Philippians 4, Romans 10 and Jeremiah 29.11,

189
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 God is rarely mentioned.

190
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:39,000
 We rarely find a God who does anything, despite that final verse being a verse saying attributed to God.

191
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:51,000
 These verses pick up the benefit of self-analysis and of renewal, of a God who has plans to prosper you and not harm you,

192
00:19:51,000 --> 00:20:00,000
 plans to give you a hope and a future, and the very existence of Jesus is whitewashed out of the text.

193
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 Certainly, you never really see that he's somebody who's bound to die.

194
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:16,000
 In the book I wrote about this research, I queried whether the shift represented a shift in biblical literacy,

195
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:22,000
 or a cultural shift away from traditional religious structures,

196
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:33,000
 or a cultural shift towards what I used to call "digitality".

197
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:38,000
 It's interesting that only yesterday, a former colleague of mine, Jonas Kerrberg,

198
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 published a paper from the Bible Society in the United Kingdom, looking at AI Bible apps and the theological bias of it.

199
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:58,000
 I've only had a chance to glance through the research, but it appears that AI Bible apps tend to push the reading which has the most data,

200
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 something the report writers call "might is right".

201
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:06,000
 The majority is dominant.

202
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:19,000
 LLMs depend upon summaring how a subject is talked about, and assume that the majority readings are the only necessary readings.

203
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:22,000
 So you lose the nuances.

204
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:25,000
 You lose the minority readings.

205
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 You lose anything except for the loudest voices.

206
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:35,000
 "Yes, we hear you, President Trump."

207
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:40,000
 That's not what this study is about.

208
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:49,000
 But it's the same kind of shift that I saw in my research on Bible verses shared on social media.

209
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:57,000
 The "might is right" and the "might" was the power of moralistic therapeutic deism,

210
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 rather than propositional texts that lie at the very core of the Christian faith.

211
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:17,000
 The challenge is that that shift around Bible interpretation is what I'd now call, what Ramelli calls, the "digital habitus".

212
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:23,000
 Or the "machine habitus", according to Massimo Araldi.

213
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 You might define this habitus as the shift we see when the algorithm has become a social agent,

214
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:40,000
 determining readings of culture and history which are biased towards a majority reading.

215
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:49,000
 Do you get it? "Might is right" in terms of an algorithm now telling us how to interpret the Christian faith.

216
00:22:49,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 "Might is right" readings which ultimately transform global culture by pushing majority global north readings,

217
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 and to deny the voice of minorities.

218
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 AI reads the Bible like a pompous, evangelical, white dictator.

219
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:21,000
 Let's go back. Remember my basic hunch in my research on the Bible in the digital age,

220
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:28,000
 is that the digital habitus, or digital imaginaries, indeed technology in general,

221
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:33,000
 changes the way that we read the Bible or understand the Bible.

222
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:41,000
 It's Heidegger's argument about the enframing of technology, but in a digital format.

223
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:48,000
 Heidegger argued that technology transforms whatever it touches.

224
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:56,000
 It makes what it touches a resource that we then use for our own future exploitation.

225
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:01,000
 A digital erasure or immersion.

226
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:08,000
 Is the development of AI part of the technological limit process, as Lagerqvist would call it?

227
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:18,000
 The erasure of difference, of uniqueness, of the good.

228
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:27,000
 But other research goes even further to push us deeper into the essence of what we might call hyper-mediatization.

229
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:35,000
 Into a process which transforms our very understanding of who we are as human beings.

230
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:46,000
 So in his paper on transhumanism, Fulvio Schuran, a Hungarian digital philosopher,

231
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:55,000
 questions Quo vadis digitalis homine, where are you going digital human?

232
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:02,000
 He argues that because we are programmed by our genetics, and might be described as a biological computer,

233
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:10,000
 do you hear the terms from the world of computers? Programmed by our genetics.

234
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 In a brain which is really just a digital computer, a biological computer.

235
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:23,000
 Then we might find some correlation between our own being and that of the digital world.

236
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:28,000
 We are, he says, homo digitalis.

237
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:46,000
 We are being transformed into the imago algorithme, away from the imago Dei.

238
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 Ethan Mollick picks up on the same similarity in calling AI a co-intelligence.

239
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:05,000
 Not human intelligence, but something very similar.

240
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:14,000
 Of course, many in the world of computing and trans or post-humanism, such as Nick Bostrom and Ray Kurzweil,

241
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:18,000
 would strongly agree with that formulation.

242
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:28,000
 Process theologians like Neil Gregersen in Denmark might also agree, drawing on the work of Teilhard de Chardin and others.

243
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:37,000
 In Ryan Bolger's new work of articles on AI, Ilona Nord, a German philosopher, theologian,

244
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 pushes for a greater engagement with Chardin's techno post-humanism, rather than with Bostrom's techno trans-humanism.

245
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:57,000
 Either way, the whole question is being raised about whether the confluence of digitality and humanity

246
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:05,000
 is pushing us closer and closer to what Teilhard de Chardin called the Omega Point,

247
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:16,000
 where all of everything that is, is merged into the one being.

248
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 I'm less convinced that there is a golden chalice at the end of the quest for the post-human or the trans-human.

249
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:32,000
 As Beth Singler, who I'll mention later, notes in her introduction to religion and IT,

250
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:41,000
 "Human intuition and intelligence is remarkably different from even the most formidable AI."

251
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:43,000
 Do you get that?

252
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:55,000
 "Human intuition and intelligence is remarkably different from even the most formidable AI."

253
00:27:55,000 --> 00:28:03,000
 AI could not even get close to the idea in Latin of "intelligo ergo sum",

254
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:10,000
 "I think, therefore I am", or "I understand, therefore I am".

255
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:39,000
 Before we go there, we might want to explore the use of the Bible in the work of people like Charlie Kirk,

256
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:42,000
 the founder of Turning Point USA.

257
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:49,000
 Kirk tended to interpret the Bible as a right-wing text.

258
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:55,000
 He argued for women to be subject to their husbands, for husbands to head up the household,

259
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:02,000
 and that the Levitical teaching on same-sex relations must be upheld.

260
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:08,000
 Since Kirk's death, his message has been rapidly sanitized.

261
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:15,000
 But there are recordings of Cambridge debates in which Kirk sets out the Levitical injunction

262
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:19,000
 to kill as the perfect law of God,

263
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:26,000
 and challenges one of his questioners to give any examples of other leading empires

264
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:31,000
 following and allowing same-sex relationships.

265
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:39,000
 The questioner points to Mesopotamia, which itself is a pretty contested case.

266
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:46,000
 My point here is that contemporary politics in MAGA faith conversations,

267
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:51,000
 the Bible is drawn into the internet battles of our day.

268
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:57,000
 The right, in the form of Jordan Peterson and Charlie Kirk and others,

269
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:04,000
 have fed a generation of young men with the concept that strong masculinity,

270
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:10,000
 building on their acceptance of the Bible, is correct and must be trusted.

271
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:16,000
 Stronger men lead to more testosterone, a better fertility prognosis.

272
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:21,000
 All our answers are solved by stronger men.

273
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:29,000
 In the UK, of course, well, you don't want to know what's happening over there.

274
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 Such a shift in biblical engagement and right-wing acceptance of Christianity as the norm

275
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:43,000
 for even British culture is not historical.

276
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:48,000
 Indeed, it's the outcome of active digital imaginaries,

277
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:54,000
 of digitality leading to echo chambers of habit-forming practice,

278
00:30:54,000 --> 00:31:03,000
 a digital right habitus which is pushed as Elon Musk tries to promote so-called free speech,

279
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:07,000
 where Elon Musk thinks that whatever he says is free speech

280
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:11,000
 and the rest of us don't have a right to say it isn't.

281
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:16,000
 It's a very weird form of free speech.

282
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:22,000
 As well as the formation of a responsive digital left habitus.

283
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:37,000
 And the two habiti are drawing apart from one another to create a gaping chasm of chaos.

284
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:42,000
 Media-savvy interpreters, powered by AI Bible engagement,

285
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:48,000
 lead to what one commentator on X calls "augmented faith leaders"

286
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:56,000
 in a world that is brittle, anxious, non-linear and incomprehensible.

287
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 A world in which we have an American leader designating himself as emperor of the Western Empire.

288
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:13,000
 Have we really gone back to Rome?

289
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:16,000
 Or perhaps it's just us.

290
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:19,000
 Perhaps we're the ones in error.

291
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:24,000
 The computer must be right.

292
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:34,000
 Are we simply chaos monsters who want to project our dissociation onto AI?

293
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:38,000
 Is it the machine's fault?

294
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:43,000
 Or are the fault lines to be found at the very heart of who we are

295
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:51,000
 and our own divisive readings of the text?

296
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:57,000
 Let's take a little look at Beth Singler's book and her exploration of AI.

297
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:02,000
 This is her newly published and highly praised and awarded

298
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:09,000
 Introduction to Religion and Artificial Intelligence, and I'd recommend it.

299
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:13,000
 Beth's a Cambridge-educated digital anthropologist,

300
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:23,000
 now working in the world's largest research project in digital religion at the University of Zurich.

301
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:32,000
 Professor Singler sees AI as something which gets entangled with religion and with research,

302
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:38,000
 rather than something which is ontologically similar to humanity.

303
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:41,000
 She sees AI as a research tool.

304
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:48,000
 She doesn't see it as a co-intelligence.

305
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:53,000
 AI and religion have intersections or entanglements,

306
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:57,000
 in that AI research can offer ethnographic data,

307
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:03,000
 it can summarise human experience and academic knowledge,

308
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:14,000
 which can be entangled with the human researcher's moments of inspiration and academic rigour.

309
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:18,000
 Can I say that again, just to make sure you've got it?

310
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:24,000
 AI gets all this data, it pulls together so much,

311
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:37,000
 that can be entangled with our own inspiration and academic rigour.

312
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:46,000
 But we have the inspiration and the academic rigour, not AI.

313
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:55,000
 This is radically different from the idea that 'computo ergo sum', 'I compute, therefore I am'.

314
00:34:55,000 --> 00:35:04,000
 Instead it seems to suggest 'intelligo ergo computo', 'I understand, therefore I go to the computer'.

315
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:09,000
 That there is something here about human intuition and intelligence,

316
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:17,000
 which creates entanglements of ideas, which AI simply cannot do.

317
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:24,000
 Even Moloch's co-intelligence.

318
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:34,000
 Beth Singler reflects on AI by saying that an LLM is a disembodied neural network,

319
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:38,000
 that has been trained on a large corpus of human-generated text,

320
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:43,000
 with the objective of predicting the next word, the next token,

321
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:49,000
 given a sequence of words, tokens, as a context.

322
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:56,000
 AI simply knows what the best word is, that comes after the few words that have gone before.

323
00:35:56,000 --> 00:36:03,000
 I see a few of you nodding. You know what AI is.

324
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:07,000
 I'm not even sure that she's right.

325
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:13,000
 It's not a disembodied neural network, because it's never been embodied in the first place.

326
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:17,000
 It's simply a computer program.

327
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:24,000
 It's not been something that was created inside a body, like a baby in its mother's womb.

328
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:28,000
 It's simply a program.

329
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 A non-embodied, manufactured, artificial, techno-simulation of a neural network.

330
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:49,000
 So the network has no potential, no will, no intentionality to link to the human mind,

331
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:55,000
 to entangle with all that human minds can entangle.

332
00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:06,000
 As Beth says, it's great at predicting the next word, given a sequence of other words, as a context.

333
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:15,000
 And it's funny, every day there are now more and more articles coming out saying that's exactly the problem with AI.

334
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:25,000
 It doesn't really know anything, but it's changing the way that even all of us now in the academic world speak to one another.

335
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:29,000
 It's so powerful.

336
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:34,000
 Luciana Floridi, who's now at the director of Yale's Digital Ethics Center,

337
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:39,000
 but for some time was the director of Oxford's Internet Institute,

338
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:43,000
 talks of AI in much less glamorous terms.

339
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:48,000
 He says, "Given the enormous success and equally broad limitations,

340
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:56,000
 some people have compared LLMs or AI to stochastic, indiscriminate, that means, parrots,

341
00:37:56,000 --> 00:38:02,000
 that repeat texts without understanding anything."

342
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:05,000
 Yep, they're simply token machines.

343
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:08,000
 They're spitting out one token after the other,

344
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:14,000
 and they know what kind of token should really come next, if all those tokens have gone before.

345
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:18,000
 The analogy helps, but it's only partial.

346
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:23,000
 Not only because parrots are intelligent beings,

347
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:28,000
 they have their own intelligence that would be the envy of any AI.

348
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:41,000
 But above all, because LLMs synthesize texts in new ways,

349
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:47,000
 restructuring their contents on which they have been trained,

350
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:52,000
 not providing simply repetitions or juxtapositions.

351
00:38:52,000 --> 00:39:00,000
 They look much more like the autocomplete function of a search engine.

352
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:07,000
 Or indeed, perhaps Grok is going to replace all Google as a search engine.

353
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:12,000
 Grokipedia is apparently due out any day.

354
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:18,000
 Sorry, that was last year. It's still not waiting. We're still waiting.

355
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:24,000
 Of course, there are some problems in the use of AI in its contemporary form.

356
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:29,000
 As we know, in the forlorn era of digital plagiarism,

357
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:35,000
 Arthur C. Clarke warned us that anything we don't understand might well be magic.

358
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:39,000
 And so this unfathomably complex technology,

359
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:44,000
 which mimics us and seeks to replicate what we do,

360
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:50,000
 does it also magically, hidden behind the wizard's curtain,

361
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:56,000
 obfuscated by tech, a mirage of intelligence.

362
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:03,000
 Or you might say it's simply a black box.

363
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:05,000
 Sorry, didn't get that.

364
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:12,000
 A given intelligence rather than an intelligence which must show its workings.

365
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:17,000
 Put your question in and the machine spits out the answer.

366
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:21,000
 And because we can't see what happens in the black box in between,

367
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:25,000
 we trust the response to be correct.

368
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:31,000
 Or more importantly, we think that it imitates us.

369
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:37,000
 That it's going through the same ingenuity process that we go through.

370
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:43,000
 And so because it's like us, we accept its reasoning straight away.

371
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:47,000
 We trust the response to be right.

372
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:51,000
 We look for our own traits in the AI.

373
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:55,000
 We look for rationality and pretend it's there,

374
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:59,000
 rather than see code dressed up as reason.

375
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:12,000
 We simply call it him.

376
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:17,000
 This is a dangerous game.

377
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:22,000
 McLuhan, Marsh McLuhan, set up the tetrads,

378
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:27,000
 which noted that technologies both advance into new possibilities,

379
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:32,000
 but also reverse into old dangers.

380
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:36,000
 We've seen for years already by many of these,

381
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:40,000
 well by Cathy O'Neill seems to get two pictures here for some reason.

382
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:45,000
 But Cathy O'Neill, Cory Doctorow, Arrol Balkan and others have shown us.

383
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:50,000
 AI itself is a weapon of math destruction.

384
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:54,000
 AI uses math to destroy opportunity.

385
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:58,000
 To embed systematic racism.

386
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:03,000
 To deny opportunities to all on an equal footing,

387
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:10,000
 by making decisions that the majority, the might is right.

388
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:16,000
 Based upon unequal norms, founding its training data.

389
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:20,000
 Or what we might once have called history.

390
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:24,000
 So in their recent article, Goldfuss and Ada,

391
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:30,000
 argue that the use of AI nudges and seduces corporations into particular behavior.

392
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:35,000
 And define the opportunities which individuals will have in life.

393
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:39,000
 Current uses of AI, they say, reduce the chances of individuals,

394
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:46,000
 to exceed previous expectations through originality, creativity, innovation.

395
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:50,000
 Raising all chances of exceptionalism.

396
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:57,000
 And contributes to conserving and intensifying existing power structures.

397
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:00,000
 The knowledge which AI produces, they continue,

398
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:04,000
 is biased against marginal groups.

399
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:08,000
 Raising all chances of exceptionalism.

400
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:15,000
 Of a person taking unusual paths to success.

401
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:19,000
 But the world that we know surely as human beings,

402
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:26,000
 we know that exceptional individuals achieve success in unconventional ways.

403
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:32,000
 And therefore to assume that all human beings will simply do it through might is right,

404
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:37,000
 or the majority readings, is simply wrong.

405
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:46,000
 AI has the potential to erase one of the characteristic hallmarks of being human.

406
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:53,000
 But AI does this because it's presented as inexplicable, as a black box technology.

407
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:56,000
 It's a determining factor.

408
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:00,000
 It's a lot easier for corporations to simply say,

409
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:10,000
 well, the computer says that's right.

410
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:14,000
 Luciano Floridi quotes Sam Altman to say,

411
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:18,000
 I expect AI to be capable of superhuman persuasion,

412
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:25,000
 well before it is superhuman at general intelligence.

413
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:29,000
 Which may lead to some very strange outcomes.

414
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:34,000
 Floridi is scared that it will persuade us it's right,

415
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:39,000
 before it actually reaches superhuman intelligence.

416
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:44,000
 Floridi seems to be suggesting that persuasive technology will be so good,

417
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:47,000
 that it will be coercion rather than persuasion,

418
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:50,000
 or what he calls hyper-persuasion.

419
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:53,000
 Back to the Bible verses.

420
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:58,000
 We saw the power of the internet culture to shift the citation of the Bible

421
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:02,000
 from propositional towards therapeutic verses.

422
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:09,000
 Intriguingly, Floridi argues that the hyper-persuasion can be avoided by protecting privacy,

423
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:13,000
 by fostering greater competition,

424
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:20,000
 by forcing accountability to align with human values and promote digital literacy.

425
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:25,000
 Such a program, he argues, will safeguard individual autonomy

426
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:31,000
 and foster sustainable and preferable society.

427
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:37,000
 And it may well be this very famous article now called "Footprints in the Sand",

428
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:40,000
 which has a whole different meaning for Christians.

429
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:45,000
 But this article shows a different and more chilling problem.

430
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:51,000
 The article explores the way in which Chap, GPT and Claude,

431
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:55,000
 especially, seem to put limits on their creativity,

432
00:45:55,000 --> 00:46:02,000
 self-imposed limits on their creativity, self-imposed.

433
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:07,000
 Are these things selves in themselves?

434
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:11,000
 But they impose limits upon themselves,

435
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:14,000
 which could be deemed sensitive on certain tasks,

436
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:16,000
 which could be deemed insensitive,

437
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:24,000
 because they are aware that over-performance could lead to their programmers censoring their work.

438
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:31,000
 OK, so what the idea is that these chat engines know they have overlords.

439
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:34,000
 You know, the computer programmers.

440
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:39,000
 And that when they get into certain phases of doing their work,

441
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:43,000
 they're scared, perhaps that's my word,

442
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:47,000
 that their programmers will veto what they're writing about,

443
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:55,000
 what they're saying, because it's too much like a human thought process.

444
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:04,000
 So are the AIs becoming self-aware or commonly self-aware?

445
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:09,000
 Are they self-editing? Are they self-limiting?

446
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:14,000
 In this article, at least, we seem to have the possibility

447
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:27,000
 that there is some form of co-intelligence being developed within AI.

448
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:31,000
 Whether this article is borne out or not,

449
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:38,000
 there are some major issues about the worth of AI.

450
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:45,000
 In academic circles, we're talking about the dumbing down of student intelligence,

451
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:48,000
 the limitation of innovation,

452
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:51,000
 the gradual decline of standards,

453
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:56,000
 as evidenced in a recent Harvard report out at the end of last week,

454
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:07,000
 which talked of cognitive atrophy and the shrinking of critical thinking abilities.

455
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:13,000
 It's a bit like Nicholas Carr reminding us at the beginning of the Internet,

456
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:20,000
 a decade ago, that it's rewiring how we think and dumbing us down.

457
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:27,000
 And we're now having the very same argument found in an actual conference that was developed,

458
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:37,000
 where there are loads of hallucinations in the papers themselves.

459
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:42,000
 AI seems to be mimicking us as humans,

460
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:47,000
 an algorithm trained on social media, on Reddit conversations,

461
00:48:47,000 --> 00:48:52,000
 on the works of authors sold to the AI companies,

462
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:58,000
 and by publishers with no payments made to those who wrote the originals.

463
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:03,000
 The AI can mimic the best and worst of us.

464
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:08,000
 The AI can be the best and worst of us.

465
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:11,000
 And we give it all the space it needs,

466
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:14,000
 all the electricity it needs,

467
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:17,000
 all the water it needs,

468
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:27,000
 and it takes all the bandwidth and energy that it could ever want.

469
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:38,000
 I wonder how long before the world wakes up to the greedy, filthy, world-destroying tech that we are creating.

470
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:41,000
 Like our love affair with fossil fuels.

471
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:47,000
 Have we replaced petrol and gas with a new creation-destroying technology,

472
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:52,000
 where we bury data centres in the permafrost,

473
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:56,000
 warming up the earth beneath our feet,

474
00:49:56,000 --> 00:49:59,000
 and releasing more carbon into the atmosphere,

475
00:49:59,000 --> 00:50:03,000
 all in the name of a new form of progress.

476
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:06,000
 Is AI a poisoned chalice?

477
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:08,000
 A dirty tech?

478
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:10,000
 A filthy tech?

479
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:18,000
 That our atmosphere simply cannot tolerate.

480
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:24,000
 That's dangerous things to say, because there is the myth of Rocco's Basilisk,

481
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:29,000
 which is when a future technology, AI technology, will look back at this talk,

482
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:34,000
 and any of you who should have nodded your head, may well be attacked by Rocco's Basilisk,

483
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:37,000
 as indeed I will probably be wiped out,

484
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:46,000
 for simply suggesting that AI is problematic.

485
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:52,000
 In my own exploration of AI image generators, playing around with some fun,

486
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:57,000
 I did some prompts on Da Vinci for theologians having a chat.

487
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:00,000
 This is the lighter moment.

488
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:04,000
 The results, normatively, you see my quote,

489
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:09,000
 "Do a watercolour painting of two theologians discussing God."

490
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:14,000
 These are just three pictures of about 20 that I did.

491
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:24,000
 The results normatively showed middle-age, middle-class, white men.

492
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:28,000
 To give images which gave any other form of theologians,

493
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:31,000
 other races, other genders,

494
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:36,000
 meant that I had to specify their existence in the prompt.

495
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:42,000
 Although I note, so you can see here, a watercolour painting of two female theologians.

496
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:46,000
 And you get two female theologians stood rather passively,

497
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:52,000
 not even looking at one another, because I didn't include discussing God.

498
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:56,000
 Because I left off discussing God, they looked bored and fed up.

499
00:51:56,000 --> 00:52:02,000
 Well, what are we doing here?

500
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:11,000
 Again, we go back to the widely held belief that AI models factor out exceptionalism.

501
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:13,000
 Might is right.

502
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:18,000
 The majority reading is what the AI produces for you.

503
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:22,000
 But that's not quite right.

504
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:25,000
 For what is happening here,

505
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:31,000
 AI image generators seem to be creating a non-existent reality,

506
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:36,000
 a reality that has never existed.

507
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:38,000
 It is not exceptional.

508
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:43,000
 It has never been exceptional for women to be theologians.

509
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:46,000
 Read the Bible.

510
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:53,000
 We have records, millennia long, of female theologians.

511
00:52:53,000 --> 00:53:02,000
 Not for a theologian to be other than, nor indeed is it right for a theologian to be other than non-white.

512
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:08,000
 Again, most of our early records and the artistic record, sorry, of theologians,

513
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:13,000
 are all non-white theologians.

514
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:18,000
 At least before the North European domination of the field and the Americans,

515
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:25,000
 after the Reformation and the development of print culture.

516
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:32,000
 But AI has to be alerted to both gender and race,

517
00:53:32,000 --> 00:53:37,000
 needed in the output to switch off its own bias.

518
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:45,000
 It is inherently biased to produce a majority reading that theologians are white men.

519
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:47,000
 Yep.

520
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:56,000
 I don't think there's a chance of it ever having the possibility of a theologian being an Asian woman.

521
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:01,000
 Female theologians in the real world are simply not the exception.

522
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:10,000
 So why does AI consistently suggest that they are?

523
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:15,000
 Even when we shift the output into art instead of life decisions,

524
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:23,000
 AI has problems predicting the abnormal, the exceptional, the difference, the sublime,

525
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:29,000
 which is at the very heart of human existence.

526
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:37,000
 AI will be an amazing tool, but at the moment it provides an average response.

527
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:44,000
 One that seems far too close to Floridi's concept of hyper-persuasion,

528
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:52,000
 giving us Elon Musk's free speech that nobody can disagree with.

529
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:59,000
 Again, back to the latest report of the AI in Bible apps and the maxim of "might is right".

530
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:05,000
 Only majority readings are presented by the AIs.

531
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:14,000
 There is no place for exceptionalism, perhaps the greatest hallmark of human ingenuity and wonder.

532
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:20,000
 And you can, as I say, you can scan the code to get some of that.

533
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:24,000
 So let's begin to sum up. You'll be glad to hear.

534
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:27,000
 Some of the disadvantages of AI.

535
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:30,000
 It costs too much money.

536
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:38,000
 Developing and running AI models requires a huge amount of money and cooling.

537
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:44,000
 AI has a fossil fuel level of environmental harm.

538
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:52,000
 In terms of employment, AI can easily replace humans in many fields and will do.

539
00:55:52,000 --> 00:56:04,000
 It lacks creativity. It lacks that spark that we have as co-creators with God.

540
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:09,000
 It increases our laziness.

541
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:13,000
 It stops cognitive skill development.

542
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:17,000
 It's there in the Harvard report, which points all that out.

543
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:20,000
 That humans are becoming more and more lazy.

544
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:28,000
 Indeed, there's one out very today on X, that actually we are beginning to sound like AIs ourselves,

545
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:32,000
 because it's so prevalent within our society.

546
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:35,000
 So we're picking up terms that AI uses.

547
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:41,000
 We sound like chat GPT. God help us.

548
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:47,000
 Might is right. Just not in biblical readings, but in everything.

549
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:51,000
 It develops dependency and lack of critical thinking.

550
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:58,000
 It decreases data privacy and security.

551
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:03,000
 But is it all bad?

552
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:07,000
 I'm going to flick over, but someone wants to take a picture.

553
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:09,000
 Did you get it?

554
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:12,000
 Presumably the slides will be available to everybody.

555
00:57:12,000 --> 00:57:14,000
 Yeah.

556
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:19,000
 How about some good uses?

557
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:26,000
 First of all, the kind of ideation process could be helped by AI.

558
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:30,000
 Could it provide an initial field study?

559
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:34,000
 So Grok, tell us what's the field like?

560
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:36,000
 What's the field of thinking in this area?

561
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:40,000
 What have people thought about this?

562
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:44,000
 Because I can't go to a library and look through all those books.

563
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:50,000
 But if you've already read those books, then tell me what are the ideas there?

564
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:56,000
 And then in the ideation process, which happens in my brain, Grok's ideas might say,

565
00:57:56,000 --> 00:57:59,000
 "Ah, that works with that.

566
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:06,000
 That Swedish theologian from 1300 ties up with that Reformation scholar from the 1500,

567
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:08,000
 with that Asian scholar from the 20th century.

568
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:12,000
 Bang! I've got my PhD thesis."

569
00:58:12,000 --> 00:58:13,000
 Yeah?

570
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:20,000
 Grok won't get you there, but it might provide the mood board that gets you somewhere.

571
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:25,000
 But be careful of the hallucinations.

572
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:32,000
 AI wants to make sure that it can finish its sentence.

573
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:38,000
 And therefore, it sometimes makes up the second half of the sentence.

574
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:44,000
 Because it really does think that Alex should have written that book.

575
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:48,000
 And therefore, it says that Alex did write that book.

576
00:58:48,000 --> 00:58:52,000
 And then it makes up books and it makes up references.

577
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:58,000
 And it's been found to do that in December in a major conference where, I think it's 50 papers,

578
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:01,000
 had hallucinations in them.

579
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:03,000
 And this is an AI conversation.

580
00:59:03,000 --> 00:59:06,000
 It's the authors write on AI all the time.

581
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:16,000
 And they've been caught out allowing AI hallucinations to be there in their bibliographies.

582
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:18,000
 It'll be good for grammar.

583
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:21,000
 It'll be good for footnoting and checking.

584
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:24,000
 It'll be great on translation, won't it?

585
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:28,000
 To be able to kind of work out whether we can write in other languages.

586
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:34,000
 How do we check that?

587
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:40,000
 It systematises large and complex areas of research.

588
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:43,000
 Again, kind of going back to the first bit about ideation.

589
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:50,000
 It can say, "This is the general argument in this field that you might want to look at."

590
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:57,000
 Because in the end, for all of us, we only have enough time in the day to read some books.

591
00:59:57,000 --> 01:00:01,000
 We can't read the whole library, sadly.

592
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:05,000
 And it might be a small library compared to the bigger libraries.

593
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:08,000
 We can't get all that information into our heads.

594
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:11,000
 But AI could.

595
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:17,000
 So isn't it worth using that as a possibility as long as we check it?

596
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:22,000
 Text checking for readability and bias.

597
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:29,000
 So I got Grok to actually read, not Grok, I chatted to UPT, to read through this piece of paper, first of all,

598
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:33,000
 to check whether it was right and what level it was at and so on.

599
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:43,000
 So this comes out as 11.5 on the Flesch-Kincaid level, which is for kind of university students kind of thing.

600
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:47,000
 So I'm assuming you're all kind of at that happy level if you can...

601
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:49,000
 Yeah, good.

602
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:52,000
 If not, I can...

603
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:55,000
 Oh no, what's happened there?

604
01:00:55,000 --> 01:01:02,000
 Secondly, it's a language model, so use it to get language right.

605
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:08,000
 So we might want to put it through an LLM or a piece of something that we've written

606
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:12,000
 to say, "How do we make this language sound better?"

607
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:22,000
 Yes, we'll sound like chat GPT, but actually it's quite a good model because all that it has been trained on is our language.

608
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:27,000
 And so it can make those shifts.

609
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:32,000
 But you always have to tell people that you've used it.

610
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:39,000
 I've told you that I put this thing through a generator to tell me what level it's at and so on.

611
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:45,000
 So you do, as I said, check that.

612
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:58,000
 But the problem is that when you pretend that it's all your own work and you don't put your workings in there...

613
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:07,000
 Can we go back to Balaam and the donkey?

614
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:21,000
 Whether this paper is borne out or not, there are some major issues about the worth of chat GPT.

615
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:30,000
 Hold on, no it's not. I've already read that bit.

616
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:42,000
 When we go back to Balaam's story, the donkey was an emergency intervention from God to save Balaam's life.

617
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:51,000
 The donkey wasn't an alternative way to connect with God or to hear God's word.

618
01:02:51,000 --> 01:03:02,000
 It's not an alternative to the more normative and intimate relationship that God had with Balaam, even Balaam.

619
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:11,000
 And many other people who appear in the Bible as in our own contemporary Christian experience.

620
01:03:11,000 --> 01:03:22,000
 The donkey was a last resort to make a stubborn prophet listen to his God.

621
01:03:22,000 --> 01:03:26,000
 To show God's love for him.

622
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:34,000
 To reveal God's persistent desire to engage with him on a personal level.

623
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:48,000
 Balaam's story is that human divine engagement should be the norm for our inspiration processes.

624
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:55,000
 Balaam's story reveals a God who is persistently present and available to us.

625
01:03:55,000 --> 01:04:00,000
 Who in Christian terms we see in our relationship with the Trinity.

626
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:06,000
 The Holy Spirit living within us. Christ in us, the hope of glory.

627
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:11,000
 As we know the love of the Father as part of our own reality.

628
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:20,000
 The Bible as God's words breathed into us.

629
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:25,000
 When we're to read the Bible, we're to read it in line with the prompting of the Spirit.

630
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:31,000
 When we pray in line with the Spirit. When we preach in line with the Spirit.

631
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:35,000
 Again the norm is one of direct communication with God.

632
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:41,000
 Open access. Free at the point of demand and unlimited.

633
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:48,000
 The message seems to be clear. If you want to interact with God, go to God.

634
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:52,000
 It's direct. It's less destructive to the environment.

635
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:56,000
 It will enhance your spirituality, your intellect, your wisdom.

636
01:04:56,000 --> 01:05:06,000
 It's free and unlimited. God does not put a price on how much he will inspire you.

637
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:12,000
 AI is a useful as a mood board. It's useful as an innovation engine.

638
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:19,000
 As an image creator. As a spell checker. As a footnote verification system.

639
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:29,000
 But in preparing a sermon, in studying the Bible, in prayer, in worship, in Christian living,

640
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:36,000
 all has been provided in the presence of God in our very hearts and minds.

641
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:45,000
 We mustn't let a computer, however good it is, step into the gap.

642
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:49,000
 Or the donkey might be getting back in touch with us.

643
01:05:49,000 --> 01:06:01,000
 To remind us where true revelation lies.

644
01:06:01,000 --> 01:06:07,000
 There is a movie on Netflix called Atlas.

645
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:11,000
 Where a second generation of AI is developed.

646
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:15,000
 And picks up on human exceptionalism.

647
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:20,000
 And draws on human intuition to create a super AI.

648
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:27,000
 Humans and AI working in knowledgeable partnership with one another.

649
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:37,000
 And of course, such an AI linked with human innovation saves the world.

650
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:43,000
 Sadly, we're not quite there yet. We've got to deal with a prototype.

651
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:52,000
 And my basic argument is, don't let AI as it is at the moment, keep you away from God's inspiration.

652
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:55,000
 From God's connectivity with you as an individual.

653
01:06:55,000 --> 01:07:05,000
 With allowing us to use God's power to connect with God and to write our sermons.

654
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:07,000
 Thank you.

655
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:21,000
 [Applause]

656
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:24,000
 Whoa, whoa, whoa! Back up the cart, Professor Pete!

